Take ted cheeseman, i know we meme on him but he looked pretty good coming up. Sam eggington has a ddfentt scrap with him, ultimately beating him. Egg then goes to fight smith and just gets completely dismantled and outclassed and stopped.

Eubz has had several fair showings but never really broken through, made liam willaims (a decent) look foolish, then he comes up and smith and is consistently getting caught with shots, like the right hand that make him look totally amateur

Then obviously smith fights a p4p canelo type - does ok but ultimately cant handle the pace/power/skills

Smith really is a great visual aid for the skill gulf in boxing, and a lesson on the value of fundamentals.

If you want to play this wacky formation, someone needs to cover all of that space down the flanks and between the midfield and attackers. It could maybe work if you play complete hoofball with a target man, an AF, and a poacher. The idea being that you would outnumber the center backs and you have a strong center on defense. Hoof it up to the strikers, target man wins it and poacher and AF make runs in behind the defender who pushed up for the aerial challenge. The DM is a little redundant when you have 3 CBs though. Maybe make him a halfback (so that he backs into the D line and it spreads out out of possession) and make the wing backs attacking to have better influence down the flanks. That way if you lose the ball with the wing backs caught, theoretically the halfback would be giving you a back 4 in defense still. The last thing is that the AMC probably needs to be a roaming playmaker or something because he's got tons of space to cover. This one is difficult, I'd have to mess around with it. Kai Havertz is from my region and a few months younger than me. We often played against his boyhood club. He went to the biggest club in the region when he was 10, I would guess I played him five times or so on grass and maybe three times indoors or something. Since we all still were little kids, it’s not really saying a lot, but let’s just say that he was overpowered for sure. He was very fast and the ball seemed to be glued to his feet, he could play passes with much more accuracy than all of us, and he seemed to have a great vision, a very smart player. I often had to guard him since I was the fastest of my team and good at defending, but shit everywhere else. It usually didn’t end well, but I had my moments even against him. He never played overly arrogant or fancy by the way, no meme tricks. A very complete an rational player, very mature. He also wasn’t the leader of his team, he seemed to be more of a quiet guy who could sometimes have these flashes of hyperactivity though. I found him quite nice, I always apologized when I had tackled him too hard or missed the ball, and he always said something nice back. This sounds weird, but I think we were kind of similar as characters. We even looked somewhat similar that age. The main difference was that he was 10x as good as me back then and is 1000x as good now

In other words, nothing really happened, the conference just fell apart. Everyone decided to go into a downward trend at the same time.

Also people surprised by Purdue don't know anything about college basketball. Purdue has more conference championships than any other Big Ten school - while many of those were in the 20s and 30s, Indiana as a state has always punched way above its weight, and Purdue was a dominant force under Gene Keady, and Matt Painter already has 3 regular season championships and 4 tournament championships. They're a paper tiger this year, but they've long been one of the Big Ten's better programs.
